        <h1>About</h1>

        <h2>The author</h2>
        <p>Ankhlan Erdenebileg is a monetary economist working at a central
        bank. His writing covers reserves, gold, yield curves, FX flows, and
        the plumbing of the international monetary system. He prefers
        first-principles arguments, primary sources, and small charts that
        say one thing well.</p>

        <h2>The site</h2>
        <p>This site is a working notebook. It is also a proof of concept
        for a writing system that combines TeX-quality typography for
        mathematics and figures with HTML-native prose. The architecture
        is documented in the inaugural post and may evolve in public.</p>

        <p>Each post is one markdown file. Inside that file, fenced blocks
        marked <code>tex-island</code> carry self-contained TeX documents
        that are compiled to SVG at build time and embedded inline. Simple
        inline mathematics is rendered in the browser by KaTeX. Display
        math and TikZ figures use real TeX. The seam between the two
        layout engines is an <code>&lt;object&gt;</code> tag.</p>

        <p>The site is static HTML served by GitHub Pages. The build is a
        small Python program. There is no tracking, no analytics, no
        comment system, and no AI byline — the tool helps shape the words;
        the words and the responsibility for them are the author's.</p>

        <h2>Contact</h2>
